249
00:19:09,690 --> 00:19:12,692
We met earlier at the hotel tonight,
remember?

250
00:19:12,860 --> 00:19:15,069
Can I get you something to drink?

251
00:19:15,237 --> 00:19:17,989
You sure? Coke, mineral water?
Something like that?

252
00:19:18,157 --> 00:19:19,615
I'm fine.

253
00:19:21,618 --> 00:19:25,830
But Dave, something has come up
and I think we need to talk about it.

254
00:19:25,998 --> 00:19:29,167
I'm so sorry.
I know I wasn't supposed to talk...

255
00:19:29,334 --> 00:19:32,378
- ...but I saw the crowd and I got excited...
- Heh.

256
00:19:32,546 --> 00:19:34,672
No, no, no,
we're not upset with you, Dave.

257
00:19:34,840 --> 00:19:37,842
We think you did a terrific job.

258
00:19:38,343 --> 00:19:39,802
Don't we, Bob?

259
00:19:40,470 --> 00:19:43,681
- Terrific.
- In fact, we think you did such a good job...

260
00:19:43,849 --> 00:19:46,350
...that we would like to...

261
00:19:46,518 --> 00:19:48,352
...extend things a little.

262
00:19:48,520 --> 00:19:50,104
- Extend things?
BOB: - Yes.

263
00:19:50,272 --> 00:19:51,898
Extend them.

264
00:19:54,234 --> 00:19:55,610
Come here.

265
00:20:05,996 --> 00:20:07,163
Try it out.

266
00:20:12,544 --> 00:20:14,670
- Try it out?
ALAN: - Go ahead.

267
00:20:28,518 --> 00:20:29,644
How's that feel?

268
00:20:29,811 --> 00:20:30,895
Well, very nice.

269
00:20:33,857 --> 00:20:35,274
Dave...

270
00:20:36,401 --> 00:20:40,238
...the reason we invited you here tonight
is because...

271
00:20:40,405 --> 00:20:43,032
...something has happened
to the president.

272
00:20:43,200 --> 00:20:45,076
- Oh, my God.
- I know.

273
00:20:45,244 --> 00:20:47,787
I know, it's difficult for all of us...

274
00:20:47,955 --> 00:20:51,290
...but sometimes we need to put
our personal feelings aside and focus...

275
00:20:51,458 --> 00:20:53,334
...on the good of the country.

276
00:20:55,879 --> 00:20:57,630
What happened?

277
00:20:58,257 --> 00:21:00,549
It's actually kind of serious, Dave.

278
00:21:01,927 --> 00:21:04,929
I'm afraid the president's
not in very good shape.

279
00:21:05,430 --> 00:21:07,932
- Will he be all right?
- Oh, yeah.

280
00:21:08,100 --> 00:21:09,392
- Probably.
- We think so.

281
00:21:09,559 --> 00:21:11,018
Yes.

282
00:21:11,186 --> 00:21:12,395
Oh.

283
00:21:13,855 --> 00:21:15,356
Dave.

284
00:21:17,442 --> 00:21:19,568
Sometimes we need our friends...

285
00:21:19,736 --> 00:21:21,988
...and even our enemies, to feel...

286
00:21:22,155 --> 00:21:24,156
...safe and secure.

287
00:21:24,324 --> 00:21:27,201
We need them to feel
like they can go to bed at night...

288
00:21:27,369 --> 00:21:31,289
...knowing that President Mitchell
is fully in control.

289
00:21:32,374 --> 00:21:34,917
We need them to feel like...

290
00:21:35,085 --> 00:21:38,004
...he's sitting right here...

291
00:21:38,171 --> 00:21:39,463
...in this chair.

292
00:21:41,258 --> 00:21:42,341
Hey.

293
00:21:42,509 --> 00:21:44,343
Wait a minute. Wait a minute.

294
00:21:44,511 --> 00:21:47,305
Wait a minute. Uh....

295
00:21:50,517 --> 00:21:52,101
What about the vice-president?

296
00:21:52,269 --> 00:21:53,853
Vice-president?

297
00:21:55,939 --> 00:21:58,441
We didn't want to have to tell you this...

298
00:22:03,613 --> 00:22:06,032
...but the vice-president
is mentally unbalanced.

299
00:22:07,909 --> 00:22:10,786
- No.
ALAN: - I'm afraid so.

300
00:22:10,954 --> 00:22:13,331
- Really?
ALAN & BOB: - Yes.

301
00:22:13,498 --> 00:22:16,292
- Crazy?
- Certifiable.

302
00:22:21,673 --> 00:22:24,216
How much do you usually get paid?

303
00:22:25,135 --> 00:22:26,594
I don't know.

304
00:22:26,762 --> 00:22:28,304
Depends. Uh...

305
00:22:28,472 --> 00:22:32,433
Usually it's a barter kind of thing.

306
00:22:34,019 --> 00:22:35,186
Is this legal?

307
00:22:36,938 --> 00:22:38,647
Dave.

308
00:22:38,815 --> 00:22:42,526
Have you ever driven
through a red light, huh?

309
00:22:42,694 --> 00:22:45,404
You know, on an empty road...

310
00:22:45,572 --> 00:22:48,574
...when there's nobody around
and you know it's safe?

311
00:22:48,742 --> 00:22:51,327
I'm not sure. I might have.

312
00:22:51,495 --> 00:22:53,037
Well, let's say....

313
00:22:53,205 --> 00:22:57,041
Let's say your mother
is in the car and you...

314
00:22:57,209 --> 00:22:59,543
...have to get her to the hospital.

315
00:22:59,711 --> 00:23:02,129
You'd do it then for sure, wouldn't you?

316
00:23:02,589 --> 00:23:04,423
Yes, I guess I would.

317
00:23:04,591 --> 00:23:06,926
Now, let's say...

318
00:23:07,094 --> 00:23:08,761
...the whole country...

319
00:23:08,929 --> 00:23:10,679
...is in the car.

320
00:23:10,847 --> 00:23:14,183
The entire United States of America.

321
00:23:15,060 --> 00:23:17,395
- In the car?
- In the car.

322
00:23:18,063 --> 00:23:19,688
I see what you mean.

323
00:23:20,690 --> 00:23:22,149
Dave.

324
00:23:23,110 --> 00:23:25,069
The country is sick.

325
00:23:26,571 --> 00:23:29,156
And you're gonna get it to the hospital.

326
00:23:31,993 --> 00:23:33,744
These are the private quarters.

327
00:23:34,579 --> 00:23:37,998
The president's bedroom is on that
side, the first lady's is over there.

328
00:23:38,166 --> 00:23:40,459
- First lady?
- Don't worry, you won't even see her.

329
00:23:40,627 --> 00:23:42,044
They barely talk anymore.

330
00:23:42,212 --> 00:23:44,380
DAVE: You're kidding.
BOB: It happens.

331
00:23:50,095 --> 00:23:52,304
And this is where you'll be sleeping.

332
00:23:57,602 --> 00:23:59,478
- Hmm.
- You all right?

333
00:23:59,646 --> 00:24:02,356
- It's very nice.
- Come this way.

334
00:24:02,524 --> 00:24:05,025
I'm sure you'll be comfortable here.

335
00:24:05,193 --> 00:24:08,362
We'll be back to get you first thing
in the morning.

336
00:24:08,530 --> 00:24:11,282
The Secret Service man
is right outside the door.

337
00:24:12,576 --> 00:24:13,784
Good night, Mr. President.

338
00:24:14,286 --> 00:24:15,619
Good night.

339
00:24:16,580 --> 00:24:18,038
ALAN:
Sleep tight.

340
00:24:24,004 --> 00:24:25,379
DAVE:
Thank you.

341
00:24:41,146 --> 00:24:43,147
Whoa.

342
00:24:49,613 --> 00:24:52,114
MAN [OVER PHONE]: - Yes, Mr. President.
- Uh, nothing. Good night.

343
00:25:06,004 --> 00:25:07,171
Nothing.

344
00:25:07,339 --> 00:25:08,797
Good night.

345
00:25:33,657 --> 00:25:37,368
ALAN: At 10:45 last night, President Mitchell,
coming home from the Monroe Hotel...

346
00:25:37,536 --> 00:25:40,496
...where he was giving a speech
to the American Legal Counsel...

347
00:25:40,664 --> 00:25:44,708
...suffered what doctors describe
as a minor circulatory problem of the head.

348
00:25:44,876 --> 00:25:48,546
Reports that he had suffered
a severe stroke are erroneous.

349
00:25:48,713 --> 00:25:52,091
Doctors report that he should be up
and back to his normal schedule soon.

350
00:25:52,259 --> 00:25:55,719
Now, let me stress again,
this is a minor medical problem.

351
00:25:55,887 --> 00:25:58,681
The president has complete use
of his faculties...

352
00:25:58,848 --> 00:26:01,350
...and retains full executive authority.

353
00:26:01,518 --> 00:26:02,601
Any questions?

354
00:26:02,769 --> 00:26:05,271
The White House classifies
the president's condition...

355
00:26:05,438 --> 00:26:08,107
...as a slight circulatory problem
of the head.

356
00:26:08,275 --> 00:26:09,608
While technically a stroke...

357
00:26:09,776 --> 00:26:13,320
...White House spokesmen say the
president's condition is far from serious...

358
00:26:13,488 --> 00:26:15,698
...and he should be up and about
sometime soon.

359
00:26:15,865 --> 00:26:19,285
Do you know how many different
kinds of laws we've broken?

360
00:26:21,454 --> 00:26:23,455
It's simple, Alan.

361
00:26:23,957 --> 00:26:26,500
We send the vice-president
to Africa or something.

362
00:26:26,668 --> 00:26:29,670
We dig up some dirt on him
and then we force him to resign...

363
00:26:29,838 --> 00:26:32,339
...and get our president
to nominate a new one.

364
00:26:32,507 --> 00:26:34,383
The whole thing
takes a couple of weeks.

365
00:26:34,551 --> 00:26:38,262
You mean, we get Dave
to nominate you as vice-president?

366
00:26:38,430 --> 00:26:42,308
- I was a senator, you know?
- Oh, I know.

367
00:26:42,475 --> 00:26:45,227
And when our poor president
has another stroke...

368
00:26:45,395 --> 00:26:47,563
...of course this time
much more serious...

369
00:26:47,731 --> 00:26:50,441
...our newly appointed VP becomes....

370
00:26:50,609 --> 00:26:52,359
Jeez.

371
00:26:52,527 --> 00:26:54,069
What about containment, Al?

372
00:26:54,821 --> 00:26:56,280
Thanks.

373
00:26:58,783 --> 00:27:03,329
Okay. We got the nurses for 50 grand
apiece, and the doctors for 100.

374
00:27:03,496 --> 00:27:06,874
- The older guy wanted head of the CDC.
- Is that everybody?

375
00:27:07,042 --> 00:27:09,543
Duane's guys,
he's got them all under control.

376
00:27:09,711 --> 00:27:11,462
Good. What about her?

377
00:27:11,630 --> 00:27:12,796
Her?

378
00:27:12,964 --> 00:27:15,507
Oh, the first lady?

379
00:27:15,675 --> 00:27:20,471
She was giving a speech at Bryn Mawr.
I managed to catch her before she left.

380
00:27:20,639 --> 00:27:21,847
And?

381
00:27:22,015 --> 00:27:26,602
I told her his blood pressure went up
after a little incident at the hotel.

382
00:27:27,103 --> 00:27:28,937
She seems to hate him now
more than ever.

383
00:27:29,105 --> 00:27:30,397
Fine.

384
00:27:30,565 --> 00:27:34,693
Everybody else is buying
the "minor stroke" story.

385
00:27:36,488 --> 00:27:39,907
Let's hope this yutz can pull it off.

386
00:27:40,075 --> 00:27:42,910
DOCTOR: These are amazing results.
I must say, Mr. President...

387
00:27:43,078 --> 00:27:44,912
...even for a man with a minor stroke...

388
00:27:45,080 --> 00:27:47,915
...you seem to have made
a remarkable recovery.

389
00:27:48,083 --> 00:27:49,583
Oh, that's great.

390
00:27:49,751 --> 00:27:51,543
I'm feeling much better.

391
00:27:51,711 --> 00:27:54,797
No signs of paralysis.
No circulatory changes.

392
00:27:54,964 --> 00:27:57,091
Your ECG is completely normal...

393
00:27:57,258 --> 00:28:01,053
...and, uh, your blood pressure
has even gone down.

394
00:28:01,221 --> 00:28:04,098
Have you been exercising recently?

395
00:28:05,850 --> 00:28:08,060
Yes. I mean...

396
00:28:08,603 --> 00:28:10,938
...bicycling and, uh...

397
00:28:11,106 --> 00:28:12,314
...weight lifting.

398
00:28:12,482 --> 00:28:14,400
Looking after the diet. Uh....

399
00:28:16,361 --> 00:28:18,987
Polo, climbing.

400
00:28:21,241 --> 00:28:22,282
Like that.

401
00:28:22,450 --> 00:28:25,953
DOCTOR: Well, judging by these tests,
I see no reason why you can't, uh...

402
00:28:26,121 --> 00:28:28,247
...return to work
within the next couple days.

403
00:28:28,415 --> 00:28:29,456
- Great.
BOB: - Good.

404
00:28:29,624 --> 00:28:32,000
Good.

405
00:28:35,422 --> 00:28:37,715
BOB: Uh, Mr. President.
ALAN: Mr. President.

406
00:28:45,014 --> 00:28:46,056
[DAVE WHISTLES

407
00:28:46,224 --> 00:28:47,641
Hold it.

408
00:28:48,309 --> 00:28:51,687
- Remember everybody's name, faces?
- Yeah.

409
00:28:51,855 --> 00:28:53,397
Keep it simple.

410
00:28:53,565 --> 00:28:56,233
Course. Watch.

411
00:29:01,239 --> 00:29:02,948
- Morning, ladies.
- Mr. President.

412
00:29:03,116 --> 00:29:04,158
Diane.

413
00:29:04,325 --> 00:29:06,285
- Good to see you.
- Well, welcome back, sir.

414
00:29:06,453 --> 00:29:09,455
Good to be back. Just a false alarm.
Nothing to be worried about.

415
00:29:10,540 --> 00:29:12,249
- Clara.
- Good morning, Mr. President.

416
00:29:12,417 --> 00:29:13,917
- Nice to see you.
- You too, sir.

417
00:29:14,085 --> 00:29:16,628
- It's good to be alive, isn't it?
- Yes, sir.

418
00:29:16,796 --> 00:29:17,838
Randi.

419
00:29:18,006 --> 00:29:20,966
Oh, good morning, Mr. President.
I was really worried.

420
00:29:21,134 --> 00:29:22,843
- I didn't know what was going on.
- Heh.

421
00:29:23,011 --> 00:29:24,928
I'm so glad that you're feeling better.

422
00:29:25,096 --> 00:29:26,764
- Why didn't you call me?
DAVE: - Well, uh....

423
00:29:26,931 --> 00:29:28,974
- You really had me worried.
- I'm fine. Well....

424
00:29:29,142 --> 00:29:30,684
RANDI:
I was really worried.

425
00:29:30,852 --> 00:29:32,436
- What's with her?
- Don't worry.

426
00:29:32,604 --> 00:29:34,897
She's emotional.
She's attached to the president.

427
00:29:35,064 --> 00:29:37,566
- Remember, you are the president.
DAVE: - Ah.

428
00:29:37,734 --> 00:29:39,943
Okay, let's get back to work.

429
00:29:40,987 --> 00:29:43,530
Sick time is done.
Let's call the... Whoa.

430
00:29:46,034 --> 00:29:48,535
False alarm. I'm fine. Everything's fine.

431
00:29:49,829 --> 00:29:51,288
He's okay.

432
00:29:52,165 --> 00:29:53,791
BOB:
Let's go over it again, huh?

433
00:29:53,958 --> 00:29:56,752
You met a girl.
You fell in love.

434
00:29:56,920 --> 00:29:59,213
- And we're going away on a holiday.
- For a month.

435
00:29:59,380 --> 00:30:01,882
- A month?
- Right. Don't embellish.

436
00:30:02,842 --> 00:30:05,844
Um, do I need to dial nine?

437
00:30:07,806 --> 00:30:09,014
ALICE:
As soon as we sat down...

438
00:30:09,182 --> 00:30:11,517
...he pulls out this ring
and I got so emotional...

439
00:30:11,684 --> 00:30:12,726
[PHONE RINGING

440
00:30:12,894 --> 00:30:15,270
...that I had to ask the waiter
to bring over another napkin.

441
00:30:15,438 --> 00:30:17,064
Hang on.

442
00:30:19,484 --> 00:30:20,734
Kovic Temps.

443
00:30:20,902 --> 00:30:23,946
Oh, hi, Dave. Where are you?

444
00:30:28,034 --> 00:30:29,701
You met who?

445
00:30:32,664 --> 00:30:34,498
You're going where?

446
00:30:35,375 --> 00:30:37,334
Cancun?

447
00:30:39,504 --> 00:30:41,964
Oh, I think that's great.

448
00:30:42,131 --> 00:30:45,551
She's very special. She's beautiful.
She's a princess.

449
00:30:45,718 --> 00:30:49,680
She's, uh, really exotic and wonderful.
Uh....

450
00:30:49,848 --> 00:30:52,349
She's, uh.... She's Polynesian.

451
00:30:52,517 --> 00:30:56,186
Well, half Polynesian
and, uh, half American.

452
00:30:56,354 --> 00:30:57,688
She's, uh, Amnesian.

453
00:30:58,189 --> 00:30:59,231
Hang up.

454
00:30:59,399 --> 00:31:01,483
Uh, she has a hang-up
about the royalty thing.

455
00:31:01,651 --> 00:31:04,486
BOB: - Hang up the phone.
- Don't talk about that when you meet her.

456
00:31:04,654 --> 00:31:07,781
I gotta go now. The plane's leaving.
Call you later. Bye.

457
00:31:08,783 --> 00:31:09,825
It worked.

458
00:31:12,495 --> 00:31:14,413
He's in love.

459
00:31:15,623 --> 00:31:17,291
Thank God.

460
00:31:17,458 --> 00:31:19,293
President continued his convalescence...

461
00:31:19,460 --> 00:31:21,795
...resting in the White House
for the second day.

462
00:31:21,963 --> 00:31:25,048
His personal physician pronounced
him in perfectly good health.

463
00:31:25,216 --> 00:31:27,217
I have examined him thoroughly...

464
00:31:27,385 --> 00:31:31,430
...and I don't believe that I have ever seen
the president in better shape.

465
00:31:31,598 --> 00:31:35,225
REPORTER [ON TV]: The president was able to
attend to some official business on Wednesday...

466
00:31:35,393 --> 00:31:39,187
...and continues to be briefed
on all areas of national concern.

467
00:31:39,355 --> 00:31:41,398
The upper house and the lower house.

468
00:31:41,566 --> 00:31:45,652
Senators are elected to six-year terms
and congressmen are elected to two.

469
00:31:45,820 --> 00:31:47,029
Judiciary?

470
00:31:47,655 --> 00:31:49,323
ALAN:
Veterans Affairs?

471
00:31:50,074 --> 00:31:51,783
- Mark Davis.
- Agriculture.

472
00:31:51,951 --> 00:31:54,536
Agriculture? Uh, uh, uh....

473
00:31:54,704 --> 00:31:56,830
Cows, cows, calves, Metcalf.

474
00:31:56,998 --> 00:31:58,624
Lawrence Metcalf. He's right there.

475
00:31:58,791 --> 00:32:02,044
REPORTER [ON TV]: So confident is the
White House about the president's recovery...

476
00:32:02,211 --> 00:32:06,423
...that the vice-president has been sent
on a 12-nation African goodwill tour.

477
00:32:06,591 --> 00:32:09,051
This is Sander Vanocur
at the White House.

478
00:32:09,218 --> 00:32:11,219
BOB: First thing we'll go
over is the mannerisms.

479
00:32:11,387 --> 00:32:13,555
Alan has worked out
a sort of training program.

480
00:32:13,723 --> 00:32:15,974
DAVE: Great.
BOB: This is the briefing room.

481
00:32:16,142 --> 00:32:19,227
It's where the president
holds most of his press conferences.

482
00:32:19,395 --> 00:32:21,396
This may seem a bit strange at first...

483
00:32:21,564 --> 00:32:25,692
...but, uh, even professional politicians
have trouble getting used to the...

484
00:32:25,860 --> 00:32:27,778
A teleprompter.

485
00:32:27,946 --> 00:32:31,531
- A teleprompter. Is it hooked up?
- No, I don't think so.

486
00:32:33,493 --> 00:32:36,787
As I was saying, nobody expects
you to be Bill Mitchell overnight.

487
00:32:36,955 --> 00:32:40,082
The most important thing to
remember is his general presence.

488
00:32:40,249 --> 00:32:41,541
- Presence.
- Right.

489
00:32:41,709 --> 00:32:43,502
Now, whenever he stands at a podium...

490
00:32:43,670 --> 00:32:47,714
...President Mitchell always has
one hand in the pocket of his coat.

491
00:32:47,882 --> 00:32:51,510
That's at a press conference. Otherwise,
they're almost always on the podium.

492
00:32:51,678 --> 00:32:53,971
Um, I'm not certain about that.

493
00:32:54,138 --> 00:32:55,597
Remember the convention speech?

494
00:32:55,765 --> 00:32:58,934
"An America,
stronger than the one we were given.

495
00:32:59,102 --> 00:33:02,020
An America,
prouder than the one we found."

496
00:33:03,314 --> 00:33:05,774
Right on the podium.
Except on "America," he points.

497
00:33:05,942 --> 00:33:07,734
You know, that is very good.

