512
00:33:58,578 --> 00:34:00,912
She walks in, you wave
to the press, she leaves.

513
00:34:01,080 --> 00:34:03,999
The first lady. I mean, uh,
couldn't I start with a cousin?

514
00:34:04,167 --> 00:34:07,127
She hardly ever sees him.
She won't have a chance to tell.

515
00:34:07,295 --> 00:34:08,837
Stop whining.

516
00:34:09,005 --> 00:34:11,798
If you can convince her,
you can convince anybody.

517
00:34:12,800 --> 00:34:14,342
All right.

518
00:34:14,886 --> 00:34:17,095
We're ready for Mrs. Mitchell.

519
00:34:19,515 --> 00:34:22,350
As soon as she comes in, we'll
move you out to the balcony.

520
00:34:22,518 --> 00:34:26,730
All you have to say is,
"Thanks for doing this, Ellen."

521
00:34:26,898 --> 00:34:28,815
- "Thanks for doing this, Ellen."
- Exactly.

522
00:34:29,984 --> 00:34:32,694
She doesn't always like this stuff.
It might soften her up.

523
00:34:32,862 --> 00:34:34,946
"Thanks for doing this, Ellen."

524
00:34:38,910 --> 00:34:42,829
Why can't you die from a stroke
like everybody else?

525
00:34:49,378 --> 00:34:51,046
What are you staring at?

526
00:34:52,757 --> 00:34:57,010
Uh, ah, Mrs. Mitchell,
we're gonna do it right out here.

527
00:34:58,596 --> 00:35:00,222
Who was she?

528
00:35:01,224 --> 00:35:04,101
Another patriotic secretary?

529
00:35:04,519 --> 00:35:06,144
Hmm?

530
00:35:07,730 --> 00:35:09,314
Thank you for doing this, Ellen.

531
00:35:10,399 --> 00:35:11,775
Go to hell, Bill.

532
00:35:13,569 --> 00:35:16,196
- I think we can get started now.
- Oh.

533
00:35:16,364 --> 00:35:19,658
You can tell these two pit vipers
that this is the last one of these...

534
00:35:19,826 --> 00:35:21,952
...I'll be doing for a while.

535
00:35:22,370 --> 00:35:23,662
Okay.

536
00:35:26,791 --> 00:35:28,291
You're doing just fine.

537
00:35:29,627 --> 00:35:31,461
[CROWD APLAUDING
AND CHATTERING]

538
00:35:43,724 --> 00:35:45,308
Wave.

539
00:35:46,435 --> 00:35:48,103
REPORTER 1: Mr. President.
REPORTER 2: Mr. President.

540
00:35:48,271 --> 00:35:49,938
REPORTER 3: Mr. President.
REPORTER 4: Mr. President.

541
00:35:50,106 --> 00:35:52,315
- Mr. President, how are you feeling?
- Fine.

542
00:35:53,276 --> 00:35:55,026
- Fine.
- Ready to get back to work?

543
00:35:56,612 --> 00:35:57,946
ALAN [WHISPERS]:
You bet.

544
00:35:58,114 --> 00:35:59,447
You bet.

545
00:35:59,615 --> 00:36:00,740
I'm out of here.

546
00:36:00,908 --> 00:36:02,159
Shit.

547
00:36:03,411 --> 00:36:05,871
Will you be making decisions?
Are you back in charge?

548
00:36:06,038 --> 00:36:08,165
REPORTER 5: Mr. President.
REPORTER 6: Mr. President.

549
00:36:08,332 --> 00:36:09,833
- Go!
- Go, go.

550
00:36:10,001 --> 00:36:11,042
Go, go, go.

551
00:36:15,798 --> 00:36:17,883
[CROWD APPLAUDING]

552
00:36:22,889 --> 00:36:24,681
Don't you have anything to say to me?

553
00:36:28,186 --> 00:36:30,687
Thank you for doing this, Ellen.

554
00:36:32,481 --> 00:36:34,649
You don't change, do you, Bill?

555
00:36:39,530 --> 00:36:41,573
She hates me.

556
00:36:41,741 --> 00:36:43,533
[IN UNISON]
Yes.

557
00:36:44,202 --> 00:36:47,454
DAVE:
Wave to the camera. Wave to the camera.

558
00:36:53,502 --> 00:36:54,544
[ALL LAUGHING]

559
00:37:10,228 --> 00:37:12,270
Okay. Okay.

560
00:37:12,438 --> 00:37:14,898
Here we go. First off,
we're gonna talk to Ted...

561
00:37:15,066 --> 00:37:18,276
...on the, uh, new
Land Management Legislation.

562
00:37:18,444 --> 00:37:20,237
- Ted.
TED: - Yes, sir.

563
00:37:20,404 --> 00:37:23,573
I think if you refer to Item 3
on the memorandum...

564
00:37:23,741 --> 00:37:26,409
...you'll be delighted
to notice that the....

565
00:37:26,953 --> 00:37:28,954
MAN:
Mr. President, slip your arms in there...

566
00:37:29,121 --> 00:37:32,207
...and the machine will do
everything your arms do.

567
00:37:34,377 --> 00:37:35,418
[CROWD LAUGHING]

568
00:37:39,715 --> 00:37:41,216
I once caught a fish...

569
00:37:42,510 --> 00:37:44,636
...this big.

570
00:37:46,597 --> 00:37:47,722
This is great.

571
00:37:47,890 --> 00:37:51,726
[SINGING THE KINGSMEN'S "LOUIE LOUIE"]

572
00:37:52,728 --> 00:37:55,105
Louie, Louie

573
00:37:55,273 --> 00:37:56,815
Whoa, baby

574
00:37:56,983 --> 00:37:58,066
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
Everybody!

575
00:37:58,234 --> 00:38:00,110
[ALL SINGING] We gotta go
DAVE [IN NORMAL VOICE]: Yeah!

576
00:38:00,278 --> 00:38:01,778
[ALL SINGING]
Aye-yi-yi-yi

577
00:38:02,655 --> 00:38:04,364
DAVE:
Good boy!

578
00:38:04,532 --> 00:38:06,616
Whoa! Ha, ha.

579
00:38:08,869 --> 00:38:09,953
Got you!

580
00:38:10,121 --> 00:38:13,498
This guy has had a rebirth.
This is a different fella in the White House.

581
00:38:13,666 --> 00:38:16,209
It doesn't happen often, Bob,
but you're right.

582
00:38:16,377 --> 00:38:19,754
There's a transformation. Don't know
what they're putting in the water.

583
00:38:19,922 --> 00:38:22,257
Nothing to do the water
or anything else you drank.

584
00:38:22,425 --> 00:38:26,386
He has faced death in the eye
and been transformed by it.

585
00:38:26,554 --> 00:38:29,472
- Your boss looks better since the stroke.
- Thanks, Mr. Speaker.

586
00:38:29,640 --> 00:38:31,099
- He's doing well.
- Thanks.

587
00:38:31,267 --> 00:38:32,809
- Tell him I send my best.
- I will.

588
00:38:32,977 --> 00:38:34,894
- Good luck.
- Good to see you.

589
00:38:35,062 --> 00:38:37,147
[AUDIENCE CHEERING AND APLAUDING]

590
00:38:37,315 --> 00:38:39,566
Let me ask you a question now
right off the bat.

591
00:38:39,734 --> 00:38:42,235
What is with President
Mitchell lately, huh?

592
00:38:42,403 --> 00:38:45,238
Has this guy been having too many
Happy Meals for lunch or what?

593
00:38:45,406 --> 00:38:46,781
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

594
00:38:46,949 --> 00:38:49,784
Let's talk a little bit about desserts.

595
00:38:49,952 --> 00:38:54,289
What you don't want to do
is eat doughnuts.

596
00:38:54,457 --> 00:38:55,498
No doughnuts.

597
00:38:56,876 --> 00:38:58,209
DAVE:
Thank you, Arnold.

598
00:38:59,003 --> 00:39:01,046
Arnold, thank you so much.

599
00:39:01,213 --> 00:39:03,340
- Want to Indian-wrestle?
- Heh.

600
00:39:03,507 --> 00:39:05,050
Whoa!

601
00:39:06,385 --> 00:39:09,512
ANNOUNCER [ON PA]: Throwing
out the ceremonial first pitch...

602
00:39:09,680 --> 00:39:11,973
...the President of the United States.

603
00:39:12,141 --> 00:39:14,934
[CROWD CHEERING AND APPLAUDING]

604
00:39:41,712 --> 00:39:44,589
[CHEERING AND APPLAUDING]

605
00:39:46,467 --> 00:39:49,719
MAN: From the nation's capital,
The McLaughlin Group.

606
00:39:49,887 --> 00:39:53,681
An unrehearsed program presenting
inside opinions and forecasts...

607
00:39:53,849 --> 00:39:56,684
...on major issues of the day.

608
00:39:56,852 --> 00:39:59,145
Here's the moderator, John McLaughlin.

609
00:39:59,313 --> 00:40:02,565
Issue one, the new Bill Mitchell.

610
00:40:02,733 --> 00:40:04,567
Two weeks after his brush with death...

611
00:40:04,735 --> 00:40:07,445
...the president is suddenly bounding
around the country...

612
00:40:07,613 --> 00:40:09,864
...with the energy of a
high-school track star.

613
00:40:10,032 --> 00:40:12,075
Is this merely overcompensation...

614
00:40:12,243 --> 00:40:15,829
...or the indefatigable greatness
of a truly great man?

615
00:40:15,996 --> 00:40:17,330
McLAUGHLIN [ON TV]:
Freddie Barnes?

616
00:40:17,498 --> 00:40:20,917
John, the illness just crystallized
his thinking about his own presidency.

617
00:40:21,085 --> 00:40:23,002
He realized he didn't have
to be a zombie.

618
00:40:23,170 --> 00:40:25,463
He can show some life,
even act like a child.

619
00:40:25,631 --> 00:40:28,716
MAN: He's showing the strength of character
he did after he got elected.

620
00:40:28,884 --> 00:40:31,970
BAENES: The guy got sick, right?
He recovered from his illness.

621
00:40:32,138 --> 00:40:34,055
He is now rejuvenated.

622
00:40:34,223 --> 00:40:37,559
McLAUGHLIN: On a political
rehabilitation scale of zero to ten...

623
00:40:37,726 --> 00:40:40,228
...rate the rehabilitation of our president.

624
00:40:40,396 --> 00:40:42,480
It's an eight. The zombie is gone.

625
00:40:42,648 --> 00:40:44,732
It's a three.
The zombie will return.

626
00:40:44,900 --> 00:40:46,526
McLAUGHLIN: Chris.
CHRIS: I think it's 86.

627
00:40:46,694 --> 00:40:50,989
- He's still out to lunch, but looking good.
McLAUGHLIN: - The answer is eight.

628
00:42:01,810 --> 00:42:03,102
DAVE:
So the, uh...

629
00:42:04,480 --> 00:42:06,856
...first lady and the president....

630
00:42:07,816 --> 00:42:10,777
What is that?
How long has that been going on?

631
00:42:11,111 --> 00:42:12,529
I can't say.

632
00:42:13,739 --> 00:42:16,407
You mean, you don't know
or you can't say?

633
00:42:17,660 --> 00:42:18,701
I can't say.

634
00:42:19,703 --> 00:42:22,747
Ah, can't say.

635
00:42:27,962 --> 00:42:32,632
So, uh, your job is to protect the president
all the time? That's your whole job?

636
00:42:32,800 --> 00:42:34,259
Yes.

637
00:42:37,221 --> 00:42:39,430
- Have a gun?
- Yes.

638
00:42:41,141 --> 00:42:42,684
Ever use it?

639
00:42:44,019 --> 00:42:45,144
Not yet.

640
00:42:55,239 --> 00:42:57,365
You know, I've always wondered
about you guys.

641
00:42:57,533 --> 00:43:00,285
The way they say you'd take a bullet
for the president.

642
00:43:00,452 --> 00:43:01,494
What about it?

643
00:43:02,329 --> 00:43:04,038
Is that really true?

644
00:43:04,206 --> 00:43:07,375
I mean, would you let yourself
be killed to save his life?

645
00:43:07,543 --> 00:43:08,751
Certainly.

646
00:43:14,341 --> 00:43:18,469
So that means now you would
get killed for me too.

647
00:43:32,276 --> 00:43:35,153
ALAN: It would be wonderful for
you and great for the president.

648
00:43:35,321 --> 00:43:38,531
I'm sorry, the only time that I have available
is the 25th.

649
00:43:38,699 --> 00:43:40,950
- You out of your mind?
ALAN: - That's the best I can do.

650
00:43:41,118 --> 00:43:43,286
I'm gonna get back to you.
I gotta go. Bye.

651
00:43:43,454 --> 00:43:45,747
You scheduled a whole
day with the first lady?

652
00:43:45,914 --> 00:43:48,082
- It's a homeless shelter.
- Oh, excuse me.

653
00:43:48,250 --> 00:43:49,375
It's gonna be great.

654
00:43:49,543 --> 00:43:52,295
Caring about his wife,
spending time on her favorite issues.

655
00:43:52,463 --> 00:43:56,215
I don't want him caring about his wife.
What about the vice-president?

656
00:43:57,426 --> 00:43:58,760
The vice-president?

657
00:43:58,927 --> 00:44:02,388
Well, you, uh, remember that First Liberty stuff
we almost got nailed on?

658
00:44:02,556 --> 00:44:03,973
Yeah.

659
00:44:05,142 --> 00:44:08,061
I just dumped it on him instead.

660
00:44:09,355 --> 00:44:11,022
- When does it break?
- Couple of days.

661
00:44:11,190 --> 00:44:14,108
Look at Dave's tracking polls.
They'll burn up in your hands.

662
00:44:14,276 --> 00:44:17,528
Seventy-three percent with seniors,
84 with working mothers.

663
00:44:17,696 --> 00:44:20,031
Alan, we still gotta control this guy.

664
00:44:28,749 --> 00:44:30,333
[SIGHS

665
00:44:30,501 --> 00:44:32,835
Why are you doing this, Bill?

666
00:44:33,003 --> 00:44:34,045
What?

667
00:44:34,213 --> 00:44:37,382
Since when do you care
about the homeless?

668
00:44:37,591 --> 00:44:39,801
- I care about the homeless.
- Oh, yeah.

669
00:44:39,968 --> 00:44:42,804
I'm sure it's keeping you up nights.

670
00:44:43,013 --> 00:44:44,639
[SIGHS

671
00:44:58,195 --> 00:44:59,779
[CROWD APPLAUDING]

672
00:45:09,415 --> 00:45:14,085
CHILDREN [IN UNISON]:
Good morning, Mr. and Mrs. President.

673
00:45:14,253 --> 00:45:19,298
Good morning, kids. How are you?
Thank you for that nice welcome.

674
00:45:23,595 --> 00:45:25,346
They're all kids.

675
00:45:25,514 --> 00:45:29,308
That's right, Bill. Kids are homeless too.

676
00:45:29,476 --> 00:45:30,727
- Where are the parents?
- Hi.

677
00:45:30,894 --> 00:45:35,064
A lot of them are in shelters, but some
of them are still out on the street.

678
00:45:35,232 --> 00:45:36,899
Shake hands with the president.

679
00:45:37,067 --> 00:45:39,902
DAVE: Hi, there.
BOY: How are you?

680
00:45:40,070 --> 00:45:41,988
- Hello, Mr. President.
DAVE: - Hello.

681
00:45:43,365 --> 00:45:44,741
- What's your name?
BRANDON: - Brandon.

682
00:45:44,908 --> 00:45:46,367
How do you do?

683
00:45:47,453 --> 00:45:50,163
One of the things that happens
when kids become homeless...

684
00:45:50,330 --> 00:45:52,540
...is they start to lose
communication skills.

685
00:45:52,708 --> 00:45:55,084
So here at Helping Hand,
they play a lot of games...

686
00:45:55,252 --> 00:46:00,214
...that encourage the kids to relate
to each other and to express themselves.

687
00:46:00,382 --> 00:46:03,801
Oh, no, poor Joe.

688
00:46:03,969 --> 00:46:07,680
He has no hair.

689
00:46:08,390 --> 00:46:10,850
Oh, no, poor Joe.

690
00:46:11,393 --> 00:46:12,477
He has no...

691
00:46:12,644 --> 00:46:14,145
CHILDREN:
Eyes.

692
00:46:14,313 --> 00:46:16,689
MRS. TRAVIS: Right. Very good.
Very good. Let's try one more.

693
00:46:16,857 --> 00:46:19,442
Everybody together now.
Everybody pay attention.

694
00:46:19,610 --> 00:46:23,070
Here we go. Oh, no, poor Joe.

695
00:46:23,238 --> 00:46:25,031
- He has no...
CHILDREN [IN UNISON]: - Feet.

696
00:46:26,492 --> 00:46:29,702
MRS. TRAVIS:
Great, great, great. All right.

697
00:46:33,457 --> 00:46:34,916
Hi, there.

698
00:46:36,335 --> 00:46:38,002
What's your name?

699
00:46:38,921 --> 00:46:41,297
- David.
- David?

700
00:46:41,465 --> 00:46:43,216
Great name.

701
00:46:45,677 --> 00:46:48,304
What are you doing over here, David?

702
00:46:48,472 --> 00:46:50,306
Nothing.

703
00:46:52,267 --> 00:46:55,019
Hey, guys. Not now, okay?

704
00:46:55,604 --> 00:46:57,146
Thanks.

705
00:47:01,527 --> 00:47:04,111
Don't you like playing
games with the other kids?

706
00:47:04,446 --> 00:47:06,030
No.

707
00:47:08,450 --> 00:47:09,742
Do you like magic?

708
00:47:09,910 --> 00:47:11,327
It's okay.

709
00:47:11,495 --> 00:47:13,204
Okay.

710
00:47:13,372 --> 00:47:14,997
Watch this.

711
00:47:20,546 --> 00:47:21,754
Where'd it go?

712
00:47:21,922 --> 00:47:23,548
The answer is in this riddle.

713
00:47:23,715 --> 00:47:26,509
What can run all day
without ever getting tired?

714
00:47:27,386 --> 00:47:28,761
Do you know?

715
00:47:29,471 --> 00:47:31,013
I'll give you a hint.

716
00:47:31,181 --> 00:47:33,099
It's not your ear.

717
00:47:33,642 --> 00:47:34,976
And it's not your mouth.

718
00:47:35,978 --> 00:47:37,311
My nose.

719
00:47:37,479 --> 00:47:39,522
Your nose. Exactly.

720
00:47:39,690 --> 00:47:41,941
And look, oh, there it is.

721
00:47:42,109 --> 00:47:44,277
See? It was there all the time.

722
00:47:44,444 --> 00:47:45,570
It went up in the air.

723
00:47:48,824 --> 00:47:50,950
DAVID:
And fell on my nose.

724
00:47:52,578 --> 00:47:54,078
Yeah.

725
00:47:55,414 --> 00:47:57,456
Is the first lady still there?

726
00:47:58,125 --> 00:47:59,417
DAVID:
Mm-hm.

727
00:47:59,585 --> 00:48:01,210
Does she look mad?

728
00:48:02,212 --> 00:48:04,797
DAVID: Hmm, not really.
DAVE: Good.

729
00:48:05,674 --> 00:48:08,718
DAVE: First cover of Time magazine
and I need a shave.

730
00:48:09,845 --> 00:48:12,096
Tough little moment with the dog.

731
00:48:12,264 --> 00:48:14,015
Here you are on the cover.

732
00:48:14,182 --> 00:48:15,683
- Oh, yeah?
- Front page.

733
00:48:15,851 --> 00:48:17,977
- That's you right behind me.
- Where, what?

734
00:48:18,145 --> 00:48:20,062
See? Okay, here's me.

735
00:48:20,230 --> 00:48:21,272
Now look over here.

736
00:48:21,440 --> 00:48:24,984
You see those 20 guys and then, bing,
there you are right behind the machine.

737
00:48:25,152 --> 00:48:27,486
STEVENSON: - That's me?
- Yeah, looking very strong and, uh...

738
00:48:27,654 --> 00:48:29,196
...forbidding.

739
00:48:30,365 --> 00:48:32,491
Have you ever thought
about wearing a sweater?

740
00:48:32,659 --> 00:48:34,744
Just kind of blend in more. Um....

741
00:48:35,829 --> 00:48:38,831
Stand up. There you are again,
coming off the helicopter.

742
00:48:38,999 --> 00:48:42,043
Sweaters make my neck look too thick.

743
00:48:42,210 --> 00:48:44,962
Really? You got a sweater vest?
You could wear a tie.

744
00:48:45,130 --> 00:48:47,173
Think a sweater vest
would look good on me?

